</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> John Graeme </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2005-03-12T07:19:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: &quot;John Graeme&quot;&lt;jdgra ... @my-deja.com&gt;
Groups: misc.consumers


A privacy/computer expert interviewed on the news the other day said
that it's hard to protect your information by deleting computer files
because they're practically never really deleted--that even
formatting a disk doesn't really delete files. Is this true, and if
so, does anyone know how you really delete files on a hard drive or
floppy disk. I thought that formatting a disk did really wipe it clean.

</POST>



<POST>
<POSTER> roger61 ... @yahoo.com </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2005-03-12T08:09:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: roger61 ... @yahoo.com
Groups: misc.consumers


Having dealt with this a little bit at work (where computer disposal is
a problem) - if I deleted a file in Windows by doing a shift-delete, or
going into DOS prompt and typing the delete command, it's still there
on disk but the operating system sees that area as empty space it can
reuse. Theoretically it could be recovered but it would take someone
with special tools and training to do it. So, for example, if you had
something on your hard drive (ransom note ?) you really didn't want the
cops to find, just doing a delete may not be enough.

Next step is the reformat, which in general writes information over the
whole disk so that it can be reused. This also may not actually write
over top of every byte - not sure on that one.

Even if you write over every byte on the drive, somebody with a lot of
resources like the FBI may be able to go a layer deeper and see what
was there before.

For this reason they make disk-scrubber utilities, which over-write
disks several times with random patterns, thus making sure the data you
thought you'd reformatted can really be considered gone. I did a goold
for the words disk and scrubber, it coughs up tons of ads of course,
like cyberscrub.com, diskwiper.com, I have no clue if those are good
products but that's the kind of product you'd want.

</POST>



