"/> Interesting subject. Twenty years I was using a mix of 5 1/4
inch floppy disk drives, with some that were 400K Double Sided
Double Density (DSDD) and some that were 800K Double Sided Quad
Density (DSQD). The DSQD drives had a smaller read/write head
and could put twice as many tracks on the floppy as a DSDD
drive.

However, if an individual floppy has ever been written by a
regular DSDD drive, with the wide head, it can't be used by the
narrow head DSQD drives. The DSQD head would write a narrow
track right down the middle of the wider DSDD track. A DSDD
drive would see both tracks and produce garbage for sure. A
DSQD drive that was perfectly aligned with that floppy could
read it though, but only the drive that wrote it would ever be
that close, and then only if the temperature didn't change
enough to misalign it slightly.

So disks had to be kept separate, depending on which drives had
written to it... and the only way to switch a floppy disk from
use on one type to use on the other, was to degauss it with a
magnet. Easy, right? Wrong...

Everyone has heard about keeping magnets away from floppies, so
I figurd a big old magnet would do a lot of damage if you got it
up real close. Not the case! I put a nice sized speaker magnet
on a floppy... and it didn't do a thing to it! So I got a
bigger one. That didn't do much either, so I went and got a
*big* speaker magnet (about 4 inches in diameter).

That didn't do enough, but it did screw up the floppy so that at
least the data was now half gone!

What I ended up using was two of those 4 inch speaker magnets.
By putting one on each side of the floppy and rotating it around
a couple times so that every part was well covered, the media
was erased.

If in doubt, the 20 pound sledge hammer is the right way to safely
erase a hard disk.

